The illegal ivory trade poses a significant threat to African elephants, with only 10 percent of contraband being detected.
DNA testing by US scientists has identified the origin of poached tusks, aiding efforts to combat the trade.
The resurgence of illicit ivory trade is pushing elephants towards extinction, necessitating stronger enforcement.
Countries like Kenya and Mali advocate for a complete ban on ivory trade, while others seek sustainable conservation measures.
The challenge lies in balancing elephant populations and protecting biodiversity, highlighting the need for coordinated international efforts to safeguard these majestic creatures.
